WEBVTT

00:06.091 --> 00:08.925
Everybody else is going.
I don't care about
everybody else. You're not.

00:08.991 --> 00:10.925
Dad?
Never mind Dad.

00:10.991 --> 00:13.691
- You are not going on
an unsupervised camping trip.
- In a backyard, Mom.

00:13.758 --> 00:16.625
- A large backyard.
- Billy's older brother's
gonna be watchin'--

00:16.691 --> 00:18.658
Billy's older brother is 15.
Can we just eat, please?

00:18.725 --> 00:20.658
That is not supervision
for nine 13-year-olds.
I'm sorry.

00:20.725 --> 00:24.325
- Is it just overnight?
- Girls and boys.
No, I am sorry.

00:24.391 --> 00:26.958
I'm so sick of
never being able to--
<i>[ Man ] Kevin.</i>

00:27.025 --> 00:29.891
- She treats me like I'm 10!
It's, like, ridiculous!
- <i>I'm treating you like you're--</i>

00:29.958 --> 00:32.558
<i>Don't speak to me</i>
<i>in that tone of voice,</i>
<i>young man!</i>

00:32.625 --> 00:34.558
Benny Ray is going.
Kyle Tanner is going.

00:34.625 --> 00:37.125
Kevin, I don't care
what they're doing.

00:37.191 --> 00:39.758
- If Kyle Tanner jumped off
a bridge, would you?
- Shut up, Carol.

00:39.825 --> 00:41.858
[ Carol ] Unacceptable.
The other kids think
I'm a joke because--

00:41.925 --> 00:45.591
- <i>We're not talking about</i>
<i>other kids.</i>
- Why do I have to--

00:45.658 --> 00:48.291
That is enough.
You don't talk to
your mother that way.

00:51.125 --> 00:53.191
[ Huffs ]
Oh.

00:53.258 --> 00:56.925
It's a bunch of kids
in an overnight tent.
Is it really that big a deal?

00:56.991 --> 00:59.725
Yes. They're not
old enough to--
Will the parents be home inside?

00:59.791 --> 01:01.458
John, support me please.

01:01.525 --> 01:05.558
What message do we send?
If you stomp away from the
table, you get what you want?

01:05.625 --> 01:08.625
- Mommy's big on messages.
- <i>All right, Carol.</i>

01:08.691 --> 01:12.725
Kevin told me to shut up,
and that's unacceptable.
Yes, it is.

01:12.791 --> 01:16.658
I think maybe we have
to explain the reason and not
always hit him with "no."

01:16.725 --> 01:21.725
Honey, I did give him a reason.
He just can't accept it because
all his friends are going.

01:24.525 --> 01:26.458
[ Carol Screaming ]
No!

02:02.691 --> 02:04.225
[ Line Ringing ]

02:11.391 --> 02:12.858
[ Cell Door Opens, Closes ]

02:18.958 --> 02:23.458
[ Sirens Wailing ]

02:57.616 --> 02:59.682
Where did you get the gun?

03:01.516 --> 03:04.249
The safe.

03:04.316 --> 03:07.116
I keep it in
a safe upstairs.

03:08.916 --> 03:12.616
<i>Kevin knew the combination</i>
<i>in case--</i>

03:20.449 --> 03:23.516
You say you didn't wanna
kill her?

03:23.582 --> 03:26.516
What did you think would happen
if you shot her?

03:35.049 --> 03:37.149
I was just so mad.

03:41.516 --> 03:43.616
I don't know.

03:52.682 --> 03:54.782
What have you done?

03:54.849 --> 03:57.316
A little face lift,
that's all.

03:57.382 --> 04:01.582
What's this? What's that?
None of it works,
but it looks like it does.

04:01.649 --> 04:03.449
And the point being--
The point being...

04:03.516 --> 04:06.916
any new client who comes
in here will feel confident
that we have all the resources.

04:06.982 --> 04:10.149
I'm afraid of computers.
Where's my stuff?
Where's my photos?

04:10.216 --> 04:14.416
I have a meeting
with John Monahan
of Crutcher and Dunn.

04:14.482 --> 04:17.649
He's exploring the idea
of using us for their
class action asbestos.

04:17.716 --> 04:20.281
- Really?
- They heard about
our tobacco cases.

04:20.349 --> 04:23.516
Asbestos?
Plaintiffs. We'd be on
the side of merit, Ellenor.

04:23.582 --> 04:26.482
And the case is huge.
You'd be able to fill
your other ear with metal.

04:26.549 --> 04:29.849
- Funny.
- But we're never gonna land
them unless we look up to it.

04:29.916 --> 04:31.749
Is that what this is about?
Partly.

04:31.816 --> 04:35.282
They want us to actually
try the case?
They want a meeting.

04:35.349 --> 04:37.882
But I think
that's what it's about.

04:42.082 --> 04:44.482
Arms up.

04:46.982 --> 04:49.116
I go into appeals
this afternoon.

04:49.182 --> 04:51.482
You got the video?
We got it.

04:53.349 --> 04:56.316
So we have a chance.
With the video,
we got a shot, right?

04:56.382 --> 04:59.282
I'd go so far as
to even say a good chance.

04:59.349 --> 05:01.949
But courts don't like to put
killers back on the street.

05:02.016 --> 05:03.949
But the Constitution--

05:04.016 --> 05:06.749
That's like, uh, sacred
to those judges, right?

05:06.816 --> 05:11.749
Sacred, I don't know.
But, yeah,
most of them have read it.

05:14.616 --> 05:18.449
Ms. Gamble, this boy
is an honor student.

05:18.516 --> 05:21.882
He's never been caught in
the hall without a pass.

05:21.949 --> 05:25.282
This is a book report
he wrote about
some poetry last fall.

05:25.349 --> 05:27.616
Just take a second
and read it.

05:27.682 --> 05:30.749
This is a good kid.

05:30.816 --> 05:33.816
- Mr. Larson, you're a friend
of the family?
- That's right.

05:33.882 --> 05:36.616
I know your firm.
It's as good
as any in this town.

05:36.682 --> 05:38.949
But you're primarily
a civil litigator, right?

05:39.016 --> 05:42.416
I mean no offense, but--

05:42.482 --> 05:47.249
Well, sometimes
"friends of the family" lawyers
can do more harm than good.

05:47.316 --> 05:49.116
This boy's in a lot of trouble.

05:49.182 --> 05:54.982
He needs an experienced
criminal defense attorney.

05:55.049 --> 05:58.182
I appreciate your candor.
I do plan to find someone--

05:58.249 --> 06:01.882
Well, he should've been in
this room from the beginning.

06:04.716 --> 06:06.749
Do you know Bobby Donnell?

06:06.816 --> 06:09.316
I've certainly
heard of him,
and not all good.

06:09.382 --> 06:10.716
For this stuff,
there's nobody better.

06:10.782 --> 06:14.149
What's more,
he doesn't phone it in.
Call him.

06:18.616 --> 06:22.349
First thing,
I'd like to speak
to him and his dad.

06:22.416 --> 06:25.616
Good.
No problem.

06:26.749 --> 06:29.182
The boy who shot his mother.
Oh, God.

06:29.249 --> 06:32.149
Paper said it was
'cause he couldn't go on
some camping trip or somethin'.

06:32.216 --> 06:35.016
Where do these kids come from?
I mean, how do they get--

06:35.082 --> 06:36.916
His own mother?

06:36.982 --> 06:39.582
Oh, man!
What happened up in here?

06:39.649 --> 06:42.016
<i>Kendall. You get</i>
<i>kicked out of school?</i>

06:42.082 --> 06:45.049
Teacher conference.
Half days all week.
Mm-hmm.

06:45.116 --> 06:46.849
Hey!
What's up, player?
What's up, man?

06:46.916 --> 06:49.049
My mom's outta town.
I'm a menace. Right, Dad?

06:49.116 --> 06:51.982
Uh, when the cat's away--
Red Sox tomorrow night.

06:52.049 --> 06:55.082
Oh!
Man, this place is the bomb!
Who did it?

06:55.149 --> 06:57.249
Do I hear Kendall,
or do we have another rat?

06:57.316 --> 06:59.516
- Lindsay!
- How you doin'?

06:59.582 --> 07:01.582
I'm all right.
How are you?

07:01.649 --> 07:03.949
Becky, you mind me leavin'
him here for the afternoon?

07:04.016 --> 07:05.682
I gotta be
at appeals court at 2:00.

07:05.749 --> 07:07.849
No problem.
Appeals for what?

07:07.916 --> 07:09.982
Sholey.
The shooter on those teenagers.

07:10.049 --> 07:12.382
Really?
What's the grounds?
Bad confession.

07:12.449 --> 07:17.916
It was bad too.
The videotape is on
your desk, all cued up.

07:17.982 --> 07:19.849
Uh, thanks.

07:19.916 --> 07:21.949
I hate to sound
like a broken record,

07:22.016 --> 07:24.882
but I don't know
how you could fight
to turn that guy loose.

07:24.949 --> 07:29.082
- He killed
two innocent teenagers.
- My dad can get anybody off.

07:29.149 --> 07:31.049
Right, Dad?

07:34.549 --> 07:37.749
Son, I argue legal rights.

07:37.816 --> 07:40.682
And you get
the guy off, right?

07:40.749 --> 07:42.949
[ Eugene ]
Lookit here, chief.

07:43.016 --> 07:44.949
Meet me in
the conference room, okay?

07:45.016 --> 07:46.949
I'll be right in.
What's new in there?

07:50.782 --> 07:54.616
I'm sorry.
I-I didn't mean
for him to hear--

07:58.882 --> 08:01.749
72326,
Commonwealth versus Kevin Blair,

08:01.816 --> 08:03.782
minor, murder
in the second degree.

08:03.849 --> 08:05.749
Robert Donnell for
the defendant, Your Honor.

08:05.816 --> 08:07.849
Helen Gamble
for the Commonwealth.

08:07.916 --> 08:09.782
[ Bobby ]
We ask, pending trial,
that Kevin be committed...

08:09.849 --> 08:11.949
to the custody of his father,
John Blair.

08:12.016 --> 08:14.316
Given it's a murder, Your Honor,
the Department
of Youth Services--

08:14.382 --> 08:17.616
- In the interests of Kevin--
- I'm sending him
to D.Y.S. for now.

08:18.816 --> 08:21.649
Let's conference this afternoon
and make a plan.

08:21.716 --> 08:23.482
[ Bobby ]
Thank you, Your Honor.

08:30.182 --> 08:33.749
[ Door Opens, Closes ]

08:34.881 --> 08:38.448
Thanks for taking this.
Why me?

08:38.515 --> 08:40.982
Well, I think
the media's gonna go nuts.

08:41.049 --> 08:45.182
He is a pretty good kid.
I'd like to work it out
quickly and quietly.

08:49.182 --> 08:51.082
[ John ]
What happens now?

08:51.149 --> 08:53.682
He'll meet with
the court psychiatrist.
I'll be there for that.

08:53.749 --> 08:55.716
Then we'll sit down
with the judge.
The big decision...

08:55.782 --> 08:58.449
is whether he gets tried
as an adult or a juvenile.

08:58.516 --> 09:00.949
Adult?
He's 13.

09:01.016 --> 09:06.082
I understand.
But when it's murder--

09:06.149 --> 09:07.982
This isn't Arkansas.

09:08.049 --> 09:11.982
The political pressure
to go adult
will be huge.

09:12.049 --> 09:15.149
Oh, God.
Fortunately,

09:15.216 --> 09:17.416
Helen Gamble, the D.A.,
isn't leaning that way.

09:17.482 --> 09:19.416
We also caught a break
getting that judge.

09:19.482 --> 09:21.749
She is completely impervious
to politics.

09:23.749 --> 09:25.882
I'm glad she didn't
grant custody to me.

09:29.016 --> 09:31.016
I love my son.

09:32.749 --> 09:34.882
But he killed my wife.

09:37.582 --> 09:41.116
It's hard for me to look at him.
[ Sobbing ]

09:43.449 --> 09:46.249
Mr. Blair.

09:46.316 --> 09:49.182
Obviously,
this is the worst thing
you'll ever go through.

09:49.249 --> 09:50.816
It-It-- It's--

09:50.882 --> 09:54.949
And I know he probably
needs me to hold him,

09:55.016 --> 09:57.682
hug him.

10:00.182 --> 10:03.482
I can't bring myself to.

10:07.182 --> 10:09.549
Would you...

10:09.616 --> 10:12.016
please tell him
how much I love him?

10:14.982 --> 10:17.849
Sure.

10:17.916 --> 10:21.016
You know what
criminal lawyers do.

10:21.082 --> 10:24.716
We make sure that
everybody gets their right
to a fair trial.

10:24.782 --> 10:28.682
That's what I do.
You know that?
I know.

10:28.749 --> 10:31.382
I'm not in the business
of getting murderers off.

10:31.449 --> 10:34.049
But you do sometimes.

10:34.116 --> 10:38.816
It's my job to make sure
that the government
can prove their case.

10:38.882 --> 10:42.149
'Cause if they don't,
if they can't,

10:42.216 --> 10:46.116
then they shouldn't be able
to put people in jail.

10:46.182 --> 10:48.249
I know.

10:48.316 --> 10:50.549
You do?
<i>Yeah.</i>

10:50.616 --> 10:54.149
If somebody kills somebody,

10:54.216 --> 10:58.749
you keep the police
from provin' it,
and you get the guy off.

11:10.582 --> 11:14.616
In your own words,
I need to hear it.

11:15.649 --> 11:18.516
I just got so mad.

11:18.582 --> 11:21.016
I went running to get the gun.

11:23.649 --> 11:28.082
<i>Were you thinking</i>
<i>you'd shoot her</i>
<i>when you got the gun?</i>

11:28.149 --> 11:32.616
I don't know.
Maybe a little.
"Maybe a little"?

11:35.582 --> 11:38.949
Kevin, I know
this is difficult.

11:39.016 --> 11:41.149
But for me to help you--

11:44.382 --> 11:46.149
Tell me what
you're thinking right now.

11:48.116 --> 11:50.916
I wanna wake up.

11:50.982 --> 11:52.882
<i>You wanna wake up?</i>

11:54.516 --> 11:56.949
I want this to be a dream.

12:05.282 --> 12:07.149
It's not a dream.

12:09.016 --> 12:11.149
No.

12:16.449 --> 12:18.449
And I would remind the court,

12:18.516 --> 12:21.916
this tape wasn't available
to the defense
at the time of the trial.

12:21.982 --> 12:24.849
No, we understand that, counsel.
Are you saying your client...

12:24.916 --> 12:27.282
would not have been convicted
but for this confession?

12:27.349 --> 12:30.316
[ Eugene ]
There's no question about it.
The State had no witnesses,

12:30.382 --> 12:32.949
even though
they lied to my client
as you'll see in this tape.

12:33.016 --> 12:35.416
Let's roll it.

12:35.482 --> 12:38.982
[ Tape Loads ]

12:39.049 --> 12:44.582
We all know you were
the shooter, Brad.
This really isn't about that.

12:44.649 --> 12:49.549
But if you help me out here,
maybe there's something
I can do for you.

12:49.616 --> 12:52.082
Shouldn't I get
a lawyer or somethin'?

12:52.149 --> 12:54.282
I think I need my lawyer.

12:54.349 --> 12:56.782
[ Detective ]
Cigarette?
<i>No.</i>

12:58.816 --> 13:01.649
If you get a lawyer,
he instructs you not to talk,

13:01.716 --> 13:04.316
this thing
gets all adversary.

13:04.382 --> 13:08.049
You've been here before.
They'll send in
some rookie public defender...

13:08.116 --> 13:11.082
who cares more about
coverin' his own ass.

13:11.149 --> 13:13.449
You get
your life sentence.

13:13.516 --> 13:18.082
But, hell,
by tellin' you to keep quiet,
his balls stay protected.

13:18.149 --> 13:21.982
You gotta think about
a few things here, Brad.

13:22.049 --> 13:25.482
We have two eyewitnesses
fingering you as the shooter.

13:25.549 --> 13:27.516
No P.D.'s gonna
change the result.

13:27.582 --> 13:32.349
And the other--
these were teenagers you killed.

13:32.416 --> 13:35.182
You're facing double life...

13:35.249 --> 13:38.016
with bunkmates who are gonna
redo the plumbing
inside your rectum.

13:39.616 --> 13:42.149
The only friend in life
you got right now is me.

13:42.216 --> 13:46.149
I'm the only one
that can help you.
Why you wanna help me?

13:48.016 --> 13:50.016
You didn't go there
to shoot them kids, did you?

13:51.582 --> 13:53.649
You only wanted their car.

13:53.716 --> 13:56.916
The shooting was something
you didn't mean to happen.

13:56.982 --> 13:58.749
I'm right, aren't I?

14:00.316 --> 14:02.016
I know those kids
weren't angels,

14:02.082 --> 14:06.449
and I know that you're not
a cold-blooded kind of person.

14:06.516 --> 14:08.482
They fought back, didn't they?

14:10.049 --> 14:11.949
You just wanted their car.

14:12.016 --> 14:14.916
They fought back.

14:21.449 --> 14:23.282
Three hours
and 13 minutes later,

14:23.349 --> 14:26.582
my client confessed to killing
Wanda and Steven Simmons.

14:26.649 --> 14:30.249
<i>And your claim</i>
<i>is that this confession</i>
<i>is unconstitutional?</i>

14:30.316 --> 14:32.849
<i>He asked for his lawyer.</i>
<i>As soon as that happened,</i>

14:32.916 --> 14:34.916
the interrogation, by law,
has to stop.

14:34.982 --> 14:38.416
That tape made clear
the defendant never asked
for his lawyer.

14:38.482 --> 14:41.982
Are you serious?
He only said--
He never officially asked.

14:42.049 --> 14:45.649
He said at the very start--
That he thought maybe
he should get a lawyer.

14:45.716 --> 14:48.116
But he never directly asked.

14:48.182 --> 14:52.882
- "I think I need my lawyer."
- I have to admit, Mr. Coffee,
you're splitting hairs.

14:52.949 --> 14:56.849
If a suspect says,
"I think I need my lawyer,"
his intent obviously--

14:56.916 --> 14:59.582
- But he changed his mind.
- He's not allowed
to change his mind.

14:59.649 --> 15:01.782
He's not allowed
to change his mind?

15:01.849 --> 15:06.716
His mind can't be changed
by the police officer.
No, it can't.

15:06.782 --> 15:10.149
As soon as a suspect
asks for his lawyer,
discussion stops.

15:10.216 --> 15:13.516
Here, it didn't.

15:16.849 --> 15:19.516
It sounds cliché,
but "normal kid."

15:19.582 --> 15:22.549
Who killed his mother?
Yes.

15:22.616 --> 15:24.782
Normal 13-year-old boys,
they don't--
I understand.

15:24.849 --> 15:28.149
What I'm saying is
I found no psychosis,
no schizophrenia.

15:29.249 --> 15:31.149
Then why?

15:31.216 --> 15:35.516
<i>He lost his temper,</i>
<i>and a gun was handy.</i>

15:35.582 --> 15:40.582
Do me a favor, Doctor,
and have the decency
to not sound casual about this.

15:40.649 --> 15:44.649
This boy,
he was close to his mother.

15:44.716 --> 15:47.582
They had a very
good relationship.

15:47.649 --> 15:49.982
He seems stunned that
she isn't coming back.

15:50.049 --> 15:53.282
Doesn't that suggest some sort
of diminished capacity?

15:53.349 --> 15:56.649
He shoots her,
but he can't understand
why she's not living?

15:56.716 --> 16:00.782
Uh, it isn't that.
Cognitively, he knows.

16:00.849 --> 16:03.382
But emotionally,
he's experiencing deep grief.

16:03.449 --> 16:05.349
And there's nothing
in his history?

16:05.416 --> 16:09.716
I've only spent
a couple of hours so far,
but so far, I've found nothing.

16:09.782 --> 16:13.016
Well, boys just don't
shoot their parents.

16:13.082 --> 16:17.082
Give me something.
You want a reason, Judge,
turn on the news.

16:17.149 --> 16:21.516
Nightlinewill put on experts.
They'll talk about
family values, bad parenting.

16:21.582 --> 16:25.816
Pick up a newspaper.
You'll see articles about
too much television.

16:25.882 --> 16:28.882
Maybe he got dropped
on his head at birth.

16:28.949 --> 16:32.549
There's no shortage of opinions.
And you can throw them all out.

16:32.616 --> 16:36.516
There must be a sign.
Sure, there's a sign.

16:36.582 --> 16:39.549
In Little League,
he threw his bat a few times.

16:39.616 --> 16:41.616
He fought at recess on occasion.

16:41.682 --> 16:44.649
If you're desperate for a sign,
cling to those.

16:44.716 --> 16:48.082
But there simply is
nothing overt...

16:48.149 --> 16:51.582
to explain why this kid
had an impulse to kill.

16:51.649 --> 16:54.916
No reason as to why he couldn't
control that impulse.

16:54.982 --> 16:57.182
You want it
to be comprehensible.

16:57.249 --> 17:01.182
We all do.
It may never be.

17:01.249 --> 17:03.782
Thank you, Doctor.
Thank you.

17:08.715 --> 17:11.516
[ Door Opens, Closes ]

17:13.848 --> 17:17.116
So, what are you
going to do?

17:17.182 --> 17:19.348
Uh--

17:19.415 --> 17:21.682
Uh, I'm not sure yet.

17:23.549 --> 17:26.648
On the one hand, he--

17:31.882 --> 17:33.916
I think I have to
charge him as an adult.

17:33.982 --> 17:37.749
That is not the way
to go, Helen.

17:37.816 --> 17:41.249
You said yourself
"quickly and quietly."
<i>I understand.</i>

17:41.316 --> 17:44.416
But I'm looking at
a pretty mature,
well-adjusted kid here.

17:44.482 --> 17:46.149
Who gets served?

17:46.216 --> 17:51.116
The reason you brought me in
is because this case
is different.

17:51.182 --> 17:55.716
It's not about win/lose.
Now, what gets served?

17:55.782 --> 17:58.182
That's what I keep asking.
What gets served?

18:00.416 --> 18:02.482
Well, let's make a decision.

18:05.816 --> 18:08.649
I'm afraid it's gonna have
to be made by you, Your Honor.

18:10.449 --> 18:13.649
Fine.

18:13.716 --> 18:15.649
I'll set the hearing
for tomorrow.

18:15.716 --> 18:20.649
This kid is gonna lose his life.

18:21.749 --> 18:24.849
Part of me hopes
you win this.

18:24.916 --> 18:28.682
But that question,
"Who gets served"--

18:28.749 --> 18:31.616
[ Sighs ]
Where my duty lies,
I gotta go adult.

18:47.849 --> 18:49.449
[ Ellenor ]
I don't like it.

18:49.516 --> 18:51.982
[ Jimmy ]
I don't even know what it is.
[ Rebecca ] It's a painting.

18:52.049 --> 18:55.516
But it's all jumbled.

18:55.582 --> 18:57.449
What kind of message
does that send?

18:57.516 --> 19:01.416
You teach kids
to color inside the lines.
They come in and see that--

19:01.482 --> 19:04.416
The message it sends
is flush is expensive.

19:04.482 --> 19:06.316
Lindsay bought it?
Ah! Got it on loan.

19:06.382 --> 19:09.682
She wants it here when
our asbestos clients come in.
Oh, please.

19:09.749 --> 19:12.482
Ellenor, don't "Oh, please."
You know it works.

19:12.549 --> 19:14.516
Clients just glance
at our track record.

19:14.582 --> 19:16.516
What matters to them
are the cars we drive.

19:16.582 --> 19:18.782
If they're expensive,
we must be good.

19:18.849 --> 19:21.716
If we look rich,
we must be winners.

19:21.782 --> 19:23.716
You really think
we could get this trial?

19:23.782 --> 19:26.482
Hey, we got an interview.

19:26.549 --> 19:29.482
Timing couldn't be better.
We're hot off of beating
the tobacco industry.

19:29.549 --> 19:32.416
Bobby's name is in
all the papers with
this kid shooting his mother.

19:32.482 --> 19:35.116
What are we talking about here?
[ Ellenor ]
Class action.

19:35.182 --> 19:37.782
Thousand-plus plaintiffs.
Even if we split
the contingency,

19:37.849 --> 19:40.116
we're lookin' at
seven figures minimum.

19:40.182 --> 19:42.682
- Seven for us?
- For us.

19:42.749 --> 19:46.482
I <i>love</i> that painting.
[ Chuckling ]

19:57.049 --> 19:59.549
Think they'll
win it this year?
The Sox?

19:59.616 --> 20:03.549
Next year.
Every year is next year
for the Red Sox.

20:03.616 --> 20:06.116
Yeah. It must be tough
playin' in this town.

20:06.182 --> 20:09.582
Fans have a million years
of frustration pent up.

20:09.649 --> 20:11.916
Wonder how they manage
to play at all.

20:11.982 --> 20:14.249
I can't feel sorry
for ballplayers.

20:14.316 --> 20:17.949
Makin' that kind of money
to play a game in the summer
and take the winters off--

20:18.016 --> 20:20.116
[ Scoffs ]
They don't get my sympathy.

20:20.182 --> 20:23.249
You're that lawyer
for that killer, aren't you?

20:23.316 --> 20:27.216
Sholey--
that guy who killed
those two teenagers.

20:27.282 --> 20:31.082
You're his lawyer.
Yeah.

20:31.149 --> 20:33.149
Can I ask you somethin'?

20:33.216 --> 20:37.382
How do you do that?
I mean, isn't it hard to--

20:37.449 --> 20:39.482
You know,
people like that?

20:40.849 --> 20:43.216
Every man or woman
gets his day in court.

20:43.282 --> 20:45.782
I understand.

20:45.849 --> 20:47.949
But this guy's pure scum,
isn't he?

20:48.016 --> 20:50.149
He's a human being.

20:52.216 --> 20:54.682
It's just...

20:54.749 --> 20:58.482
those teenagers,
they were <i>my</i> kids.

21:06.816 --> 21:09.616
I'm, um,

21:11.482 --> 21:13.616
sorry.

21:13.682 --> 21:16.782
You like what you do
for a living, Mr. Young?

21:19.316 --> 21:22.649
It's nice to see
you do draw lines.

21:22.716 --> 21:26.149
You'd never sympathize
with a ballplayer.

21:34.516 --> 21:36.616
[ Slams Newspaper Down ]

21:46.007 --> 21:49.407
It went okay.
I didn't think the D.A.
came back with much.

21:49.474 --> 21:52.107
So? We could win?

21:52.174 --> 21:56.540
We should win, Brad,
unless they want
to rewrite the law.

21:56.607 --> 22:01.340
But there is no time limit.
My bet is they're gonna sit
on this case a long, long time.

22:01.407 --> 22:04.007
And what,
not do anything?

22:04.074 --> 22:07.807
You gotta understand.
Us winning means
turning you loose.

22:07.874 --> 22:13.207
You killed two people.
Setting you free isn't gonna be
on anybody's list of priorities.

22:13.274 --> 22:17.340
But it went good?
I think it did.

22:17.407 --> 22:19.574
Yes.

22:21.507 --> 22:25.107
When I was assigned
this case,

22:25.174 --> 22:29.840
every instinct was
let's not make this a bigger
tragedy than it already is.

22:29.907 --> 22:35.307
But he committed
a very adult crime.
It was knowing.

22:35.374 --> 22:38.374
He walked upstairs,

22:38.440 --> 22:42.274
turned the combination
on a safe to the left,

22:42.340 --> 22:46.240
to the right
and back to the left.

22:46.307 --> 22:49.740
He loaded bullets
into a revolver.

22:49.807 --> 22:53.140
He walked back downstairs...

22:53.207 --> 22:55.074
and executed a human being.

22:55.140 --> 22:59.640
[ Bobby ]
If he is tried as an adult,
he receives a life sentence.

22:59.707 --> 23:02.507
Let's not dance around
that reality.

23:02.574 --> 23:04.907
He's got no defense
of the crime itself.

23:04.974 --> 23:08.274
As an adult,
second degree murder carries
an automatic life sentence.

23:08.340 --> 23:11.874
- We have to face that.
- We also have to face
what he did.

23:11.940 --> 23:13.874
<i>[ Bobby ]</i>
<i>He's 13 years old.</i>

23:13.940 --> 23:18.207
If he had impregnated
his teacher,

23:18.274 --> 23:23.974
the teacher would go to jail
and the world would be saying,
"He's a child."

23:24.040 --> 23:26.674
But because of the politics
and outrage of murder,

23:26.740 --> 23:29.407
the world says, "Adult.

23:29.474 --> 23:31.407
"Treat him as an adult.

23:31.474 --> 23:34.807
<i>Don't be soft."</i>

23:34.874 --> 23:38.607
As much as I feel for this boy,
and I do,

23:38.674 --> 23:42.940
as much as I feel
for his family,

23:43.007 --> 23:45.107
I can't escape--

23:46.740 --> 23:50.474
I can't look at him and say,
"He's just a kid."

23:50.540 --> 23:53.474
[ Bobby ]
You can say that, Helen,

23:53.540 --> 23:56.440
because he is a kid.

23:57.874 --> 24:01.440
And if you're saying
there's no chance
of rehabilitation...

24:01.507 --> 24:04.140
with a 13-year-old,
then...

24:04.207 --> 24:08.107
you're saying rehabilitation
shouldn't even exist
as a concept.

24:10.274 --> 24:13.707
He didn't steal a car, Bobby.

24:18.774 --> 24:21.140
I'll take this under advisement.

24:32.774 --> 24:34.840
[ John ]
How you doin', kid?

24:41.107 --> 24:43.974
We'll, uh--

24:47.174 --> 24:49.740
We're gonna
get through this.

24:57.307 --> 24:59.440
I'm sorry, Dad.

25:01.307 --> 25:03.140
I know.

25:22.474 --> 25:24.840
Will you tell Carol
I'm sorry?

25:26.707 --> 25:28.574
Yeah.

25:30.507 --> 25:32.607
Does she hate me now?

25:34.974 --> 25:37.440
No.

25:49.807 --> 25:52.340
[ Jimmy ]
Asbestos clients.
Show time.

25:52.407 --> 25:54.607
Here they come.
Here they come.

25:54.674 --> 25:56.707
- Okay.
So you're gonna buzz me.
- What do I say?

25:56.774 --> 25:58.707
- Anything.
Just stay on the line.
- This is so ridiculous.

25:58.774 --> 26:02.040
Shh! There's no need to panic.
I'll walk you through it.

26:02.107 --> 26:06.174
John, if you go into
a courtroom oozing anxiety,
the judge will see that.

26:06.240 --> 26:08.840
Okay, you're gonna do
exactly as I say.
We're looking for Lindsay Dole.

26:08.907 --> 26:11.007
[ Lindsay ]
Hold on.
Hi, Mr. Monahan?

26:11.074 --> 26:13.907
It's me. Um, let's go
into the conference room.
Rebecca, could you show them?

26:13.974 --> 26:15.474
Of course.

26:15.540 --> 26:18.940
The reason I'm not panicked is
a 12-B-6 isn't just viable,
it will win.

26:19.007 --> 26:20.874
Hi.

26:20.940 --> 26:25.207
[ Lindsay ]
I have a meeting. I'm gonna
have to call you back.

26:25.274 --> 26:28.040
Two minutes, you buzz me.

26:28.107 --> 26:29.840
<i>[ Door Closes ]</i>

26:31.507 --> 26:34.474
[ Sighs ]
I'm sorry it's a little crazy.

26:34.540 --> 26:37.040
I've got a panicked
house counsel in Detroit.

26:37.107 --> 26:40.207
- Well, we appreciate
your agreeing to the meeting.
- My pleasure.

26:40.274 --> 26:42.274
Cutting to it--

26:42.340 --> 26:46.340
Your success against
the tobacco company
has our interest piqued.

26:46.407 --> 26:48.140
<i>Especially since, uh--</i>

26:48.207 --> 26:52.874
Well, going up against
the asbestos industry, uh--

26:52.940 --> 26:55.774
We're facing
a comparable Goliath.

26:55.840 --> 26:58.340
- How many in the class?
- We're up to almost 1,300.

26:58.407 --> 26:59.974
Certified?
<i>[ Woman ]</i>
<i>Mm-hmm.</i>

27:00.040 --> 27:02.174
<i>[ Monahan ]</i>
<i>We've already survived</i>
<i>a motion to decertify.</i>

27:02.240 --> 27:06.640
Most of the discovery
is done. We have
a September trial date.

27:06.707 --> 27:10.474
- <i>[ Phone Rings ]</i>
- I'm sorry. Yes?

27:10.540 --> 27:12.774
Hey, Lindsay.
Been to any wild orgies lately?

27:12.840 --> 27:17.574
Calm-- Calm down, John.
John, listen. Who's the judge?

27:20.174 --> 27:23.874
Albright. Albright.

27:23.940 --> 27:25.474
<i>[ Typing ]</i>

27:25.540 --> 27:28.874
Albright.
Okay, I've got him.

27:28.940 --> 27:31.707
Has a reputation
for being colloquial.
I definitely want local counsel.

27:31.774 --> 27:34.107
Oh, good news.
He's spoken at seminars
on frivolous litigation.

27:34.174 --> 27:36.440
He'll be receptive to
the 12-B-6 and our Rule 11.

27:36.507 --> 27:39.574
Now, I--
I don't want to file
till July, however.

27:39.640 --> 27:42.207
I'm just curious.
You ever tried, uh,
mud wrestling?

27:42.274 --> 27:44.774
The reason is
he has a summer home
on Lake Ontario.

27:44.840 --> 27:48.707
He puts in a three-day
work week. He likes
to keep his docket down.

27:48.774 --> 27:51.040
Statistically, he kicks 30%
more cases in July and August.

27:51.107 --> 27:55.007
John? John,
I have to call you back.
I'm in a meeting with clients.

27:55.074 --> 27:57.574
Okay? Okay.
Bye-bye.

28:00.107 --> 28:01.974
I'm very sorry.

28:02.040 --> 28:04.774
You've never done
an asbestos litigation,
have you?

28:04.840 --> 28:08.274
No, but that's not the problem.

28:08.340 --> 28:11.374
- Can I cut to what
I do perceive as a problem?
- Absolutely.

28:11.440 --> 28:14.807
I had a chance to look over
some of the pleadings
and witness lists.

28:14.874 --> 28:18.240
Public record. Sorry.
We may have a difference
in trial philosophy.

28:18.307 --> 28:20.907
Which would be?
You seem to be
emphasizing causation.

28:20.974 --> 28:22.907
On these kinds of cases,
we tend not to.

28:22.974 --> 28:25.107
How do you prove a case
without causation?

28:25.174 --> 28:28.340
Well, I'm not saying ignore it,
but when proving it
depends on science,

28:28.407 --> 28:30.340
you're putting
two heavy burdens on a jury.

28:30.407 --> 28:31.940
One, you're asking them
to understand it.

28:32.007 --> 28:34.074
Two, you're asking them
to stay awake.

28:34.140 --> 28:36.707
Anything they don't understand,
they get suspicious of.

28:36.774 --> 28:40.174
And with asbestos,
just like tobacco,
you have a presumption.

28:40.240 --> 28:42.040
They already know it kills.

28:42.107 --> 28:45.574
The defense can't
pick apart that premise.

28:45.640 --> 28:47.640
They <i>can</i> pick apart science.

28:47.707 --> 28:50.174
I'm wary of
leaving evidence out.

28:50.240 --> 28:53.874
Yeah, that's what I figured.

28:53.940 --> 28:56.707
We're probably not
the right firm for you.

29:02.040 --> 29:03.974
Be seated.

29:08.940 --> 29:13.140
Under
<i>Minnick versus Mississippi,</i>
the law is quite clear.

29:13.207 --> 29:17.440
When a suspect asks for
his attorney, all further
interrogation must stop.

29:18.940 --> 29:21.074
The tape here
was very disturbing,

29:21.140 --> 29:23.707
seeing the police lie
about having witnesses,

29:23.774 --> 29:26.774
misrepresenting information.

29:26.840 --> 29:30.940
Nevertheless,
this kind of police conduct
is entirely permissible.

29:31.007 --> 29:35.707
And since we find
the defendant stopped short
of directly asking for counsel,

29:36.874 --> 29:40.607
we unanimously find
the confession to be admissible.

29:40.674 --> 29:42.607
The conviction
therefore stands.

29:42.674 --> 29:44.840
<i>Adjourned.</i>
<i>[ Gavel Raps ]</i>

29:48.507 --> 29:51.440
Permission to address the court.

29:53.340 --> 29:56.107
Permission to address
this court.

29:59.240 --> 30:01.107
Proceed.

30:05.307 --> 30:06.974
You people
just ignored the law.

30:07.040 --> 30:10.040
We've made our ruling,
and I see no--
I heard your ruling.

30:10.107 --> 30:14.940
<i>Uh, the other day,</i>
<i>I had to explain</i>
<i>to my 10-year-old...</i>

30:15.007 --> 30:18.840
how I could come into this room
and fight for a man
who killed two people.

30:18.907 --> 30:21.874
Yesterday, I had to look
this man in the eye--

30:21.940 --> 30:23.874
<i>[ Judge Clarke ]</i>
<i>Counsel--</i>
Counsel what?

30:23.940 --> 30:26.040
You gonna give me
a speech, Judge?

30:26.107 --> 30:28.974
Tell me how the Bill of Rights,
how the Constitution
has to count for something?

30:29.040 --> 30:32.140
I gave that speech to my kid.
I told myself that...

30:32.207 --> 30:34.840
while havin' to look
at the father
of two dead teenagers,

30:34.907 --> 30:36.874
two kids my client shot!
<i>[ Judge Callahan ]</i>
<i>Mr. Young--</i>

30:36.940 --> 30:38.974
Permission to address
this court!

30:41.207 --> 30:44.140
Ten years I've been
puttin' them back out there--

30:44.207 --> 30:46.940
criminals,
sometimes rapists,
sometimes murderers.

30:47.007 --> 30:49.840
Ten years,
all the time tellin' myself
there's a reason.

30:49.907 --> 30:51.840
You're 10 seconds
from a contempt order!

30:51.907 --> 30:54.840
Do it! There are rules!
Rules, damn it!

30:54.907 --> 30:57.107
We don't let the police
coerce confessions.

30:57.174 --> 30:59.274
We don't let 'em
beat down doors
without warrants.

30:59.340 --> 31:02.507
We don't let them
grill suspects after
they ask for their lawyers.

31:02.574 --> 31:06.474
My client damn well asked for
his lawyer, and all three of you
sittin' up there, you know it!

31:06.540 --> 31:08.174
- You're out of order!
- You're out of order!

31:08.240 --> 31:10.607
You disgraced the bench,
this room.

31:10.674 --> 31:12.707
You just raped
the Sixth Amendment!

31:12.774 --> 31:15.107
I hold you in contempt.
I hold all three of you
in contempt!

31:15.174 --> 31:17.440
Take him and
put him in lockup.

31:24.007 --> 31:26.674
I'll rot in that cell...

31:26.740 --> 31:30.440
if giving you respect
is a condition
for my getting out.

31:33.340 --> 31:35.974
I'll rot.

31:55.399 --> 31:57.932
Dad, did you hit somebody?
No.

31:57.999 --> 32:00.932
How long?
Till morning.

32:00.999 --> 32:02.632
I argued a called strike.

32:02.699 --> 32:05.932
They'll let him visit
for an hour.
I'll keep him with me tonight.

32:05.999 --> 32:08.165
He belongs in here with me.

32:08.232 --> 32:11.365
- I'll be back.
- Thanks again.

32:12.432 --> 32:16.099
So, what happened?
Sit down, buddy.

32:19.932 --> 32:23.299
You heard me talk
of your Uncle Curtis?
Jail Uncle Curtis?

32:23.365 --> 32:26.599
Yeah. You remember
what he went to jail for?

32:28.432 --> 32:31.132
They thought he knocked off
a liquor store
and capped somebody.

32:31.199 --> 32:34.299
But he didn't, right?
Yeah.

32:34.365 --> 32:38.765
And, uh, the reason
he ended up in prison...

32:38.832 --> 32:43.332
was that he fit the description
of whoever did do it,
and the police arrested him.

32:43.399 --> 32:47.632
They kept him in a room
for 20 hours.

32:47.699 --> 32:51.999
Kept makin' him drink coffee
and not lettin' him
go to the bathroom.

32:52.065 --> 32:55.799
Kept tellin' him
that if he'd just confess,

32:55.865 --> 32:57.832
that everything
would go better.

32:57.899 --> 32:59.899
And that if he didn't confess,

32:59.965 --> 33:05.599
they'd arrest my sister
and they'd both
get the death penalty.

33:05.665 --> 33:09.399
Told him if he cooperated,

33:09.465 --> 33:11.365
he could leave.

33:12.999 --> 33:15.099
And after 20 hours,

33:16.399 --> 33:18.532
they had him to the point...

33:18.599 --> 33:21.232
where he would say anything
just to go home.

33:21.299 --> 33:26.465
And he signed a confession
to a crime he didn't commit.

33:29.299 --> 33:31.332
You hate the police,
don't you?

33:32.732 --> 33:36.099
I don't hate the police.
Most of them are good people.

33:38.799 --> 33:43.199
Kendall, most of my clients
did the crime.
I won't lie to you about that.

33:43.265 --> 33:45.732
The reason I fight for 'em...

33:45.799 --> 33:48.965
is as soon as we allow
the police to use
illegal methods,

33:49.032 --> 33:52.232
sure, more guilty people
will be convicted,

33:52.299 --> 33:54.599
but more innocent people
will too.

33:56.732 --> 33:59.199
That's what I fight for.

34:04.899 --> 34:08.099
Here he comes.
Stay calm.
Everybody calm. Look busy.

34:08.165 --> 34:10.165
Um, file.
Are they hiring us?

34:10.232 --> 34:12.599
I don't know.
Stay calm!
I'm calm. You stay calm!

34:12.665 --> 34:14.799
- <i>[ Rebecca ]</i>
<i>Shh!</i>
- Hi.

34:14.864 --> 34:17.199
Mr. Monahan.

34:17.264 --> 34:20.599
Thank you for
letting me drop by
on such short notice.

34:20.665 --> 34:24.799
- <i>Sure.</i>
- <i>Listen, uh,</i>
<i>we've thought about it.</i>

34:24.864 --> 34:27.364
We would like
to hire you.

34:27.431 --> 34:30.699
Really? I am serious
about our trial philosophy.

34:30.764 --> 34:32.899
[ Monahan ]
I understand.
We're on board with it.

34:32.965 --> 34:35.931
- <i>You obviously get results.</i>
- <i>Fine.</i>
Files will be delivered?

34:35.998 --> 34:39.965
Today. I'd like to schedule
a coordination conference
for next week if possible.

34:40.032 --> 34:41.864
We can do that.
<i>Great.</i>

34:41.931 --> 34:44.732
I'll be in touch.
Good.

34:46.565 --> 34:48.599
[ Door Opens ]

34:50.132 --> 34:53.199
Let him get in the elevator.

34:53.264 --> 34:56.864
Four, three, two, one.

34:56.931 --> 34:59.732
[ Screaming, Laughing ]

35:04.832 --> 35:06.765
Be seated.

35:15.365 --> 35:21.032
For the past several days,
I've felt compelled to blame.

35:21.099 --> 35:23.665
Easy access to guns,

35:23.732 --> 35:26.865
television, movies,

35:26.932 --> 35:29.999
brainwashing children
with violence--

35:30.065 --> 35:33.499
all disgustingly denying
any accountability.

35:33.565 --> 35:36.165
<i>Blame.</i>

35:36.232 --> 35:41.599
But in this room, young man,
it comes down to
youraccountability.

35:43.865 --> 35:47.765
<i>I doubt that you</i>
<i>or anybody else</i>
<i>in this room...</i>

35:47.832 --> 35:51.065
will ever make sense
of why you killed your mother.

35:52.332 --> 35:56.232
<i>There's no rhyme,</i>
<i>no reason,</i>

35:56.299 --> 36:00.832
<i>and ultimately no excuse.</i>

36:00.899 --> 36:04.332
You ended
your own childhood.

36:07.865 --> 36:12.199
I'm granting
the district attorney's petition
to charge you as an adult.

36:16.332 --> 36:19.632
- <i>Adjourned.</i>
- <i>[ Gavel Raps ]</i>

36:43.699 --> 36:45.599
[ Sighs ]

36:55.599 --> 36:57.465
I gotta know why.

36:59.532 --> 37:02.999
We all fall where
we fall on this, Mr. Donnell.

37:03.065 --> 37:07.232
Nobody's right,
nobody's wrong.
We all fall where we fall.

37:07.299 --> 37:09.899
Yeah.
But you're the judge.

37:09.965 --> 37:12.965
Yeah, that's right.

37:13.032 --> 37:17.065
I'm the judge.
You wanna swap places?

37:18.965 --> 37:21.699
You could've opted
for hope instead of--

37:21.765 --> 37:24.099
What makes you think
I didn't?

37:24.165 --> 37:29.232
You know,
I sit on that bench every day
seeing the evil in people.

37:31.265 --> 37:35.665
Hope for me lies in the child.

37:35.732 --> 37:40.599
Hope won't allow me
to see the child in him.

37:40.665 --> 37:42.465
He murdered his own mother.

37:44.532 --> 37:48.965
That doesn't sound like
legal reasoning to me.
Well,

37:49.032 --> 37:51.532
legal reasoning can only deal...

37:51.599 --> 37:55.465
with the consequences
of what he did.

37:55.532 --> 37:59.099
And I'll be damned if I'm going
to send that message...

37:59.165 --> 38:02.365
to the next
13-year-old with a gun.

38:02.432 --> 38:08.232
This was about
<i>one</i> 13-year-old.

38:11.465 --> 38:15.065
With the power
to make you hate God.

38:24.099 --> 38:26.365
I have to believe
a child couldn't do that.

38:28.532 --> 38:31.399
If a child could,

38:31.465 --> 38:34.699
then that surely is
the death of hope.

38:51.665 --> 38:53.799
An apology lets you out.

38:53.865 --> 38:56.465
You don't get it.

38:59.432 --> 39:01.465
Did you really think
we would set him free?

39:01.532 --> 39:06.565
I'm naive enough to believe
the Sixth Amendment
means something.

39:06.632 --> 39:09.532
Liberty doesn't lie
in the Constitution,
Mr. Young.

39:09.599 --> 39:11.965
It doesn't lie in the law
or the courtroom.

39:12.032 --> 39:14.799
It lies in a man's heart.

39:14.865 --> 39:19.732
And in my heart, I wasn't
going to turn loose a man
who I knew would kill again.

39:21.532 --> 39:25.865
"The spirit of liberty
is the spirit which
is not sure it's right."

39:25.932 --> 39:28.465
If you're gonna quote
Learned Hand,

39:28.532 --> 39:31.532
try to remember
the essence of his speech.

39:31.599 --> 39:35.332
And the spirit
of your ruling, Judge,
is that you knew you were wrong.

39:37.599 --> 39:40.265
We have to be able
to sleep at night too.

39:40.332 --> 39:42.599
And you didn't sleep last night,
did you?

39:43.699 --> 39:47.932
I congratulate you
on your righteousness.

39:47.999 --> 39:50.332
I salute your ability
to look at death...

39:50.399 --> 39:52.965
and feel
nothing but patriotism
for playing your part.

39:53.032 --> 39:56.999
We all signed up
to do our jobs, Judge.
You betrayed yours.

39:57.065 --> 40:01.632
And I will not stand here
and let you tell me
what's in my heart.

40:03.532 --> 40:05.499
Now, there's no crime
to being a coward.

40:05.565 --> 40:08.199
It just shouldn't be
cloaked in a robe.

40:13.632 --> 40:15.599
Asbestos class action.

40:15.665 --> 40:18.499
Lindsay's backing up her threat
to make us flush.

40:21.099 --> 40:24.065
I'd probably celebrate more
if I were a partner.

40:25.599 --> 40:28.265
You will be, Jimmy.

40:28.332 --> 40:30.965
How you feelin'?
Your wounds healin' up okay?

40:31.032 --> 40:35.465
Yeah. Yours?

40:37.065 --> 40:39.065
You mean Spivak?

40:40.232 --> 40:43.332
Uh, no, I--
Yeah.

40:45.399 --> 40:48.232
I'm fine.
Just a guy.

40:48.299 --> 40:50.565
Another one will come along.

40:50.632 --> 40:52.332
Plenty of fish.

40:54.699 --> 40:57.199
Schools.

41:06.365 --> 41:08.899
I've had judges look
the other way before, but--

41:08.965 --> 41:10.932
But what?

41:10.999 --> 41:15.065
Some of the disgust
is my own.

41:15.132 --> 41:19.699
When my son said,
"My dad can get murderers off.
He can get anybody off,"

41:21.932 --> 41:24.065
it hit me like a train.

41:25.765 --> 41:29.365
Since, I've been lookin'
at myself through his eyes.

41:32.265 --> 41:35.465
What I do, what I am.

41:37.232 --> 41:41.299
I needed that appeals court
for some kind of validation.

41:41.365 --> 41:42.999
Eugene, the disgrace
of that ruling...

41:43.065 --> 41:46.165
belongs to those judges,
not to you.

41:46.232 --> 41:49.332
Explain that to my boy,
could you?

41:49.399 --> 41:52.032
The courts didn't wanna put
a killer back out there.
I did.

41:52.099 --> 41:54.499
Explain to him how
I'm the good guy, huh?

41:57.565 --> 42:02.232
Look, it's not always
a meritocracy.

42:02.299 --> 42:05.565
I mean, judges rule
for the wrong reasons
sometimes.

42:05.632 --> 42:08.199
Clients choose you
because of paint jobs.

42:10.665 --> 42:13.732
Lindsay landed a coup
with fake computers.
And you know what?

42:13.799 --> 42:17.865
That case she got,
every firm in town
would drool over it.

42:17.932 --> 42:20.065
It could make us
a lot of money.

42:22.032 --> 42:24.999
But what I'll go home
and celebrate
a little tonight...

42:25.065 --> 42:28.199
is that you and I
spent the last few days...

42:28.265 --> 42:32.065
fighting for people
no firm in this town
would touch.

42:34.565 --> 42:36.732
And we both lost.

42:38.199 --> 42:40.432
Maybe it's right we lost.
I don't know.

42:42.132 --> 42:47.432
But what I do know is
what makes the courtroom
a noble place...

42:47.499 --> 42:51.765
is that people like you
go in there and fight.

42:54.532 --> 42:57.065
Sometimes,
on principle alone.

43:07.332 --> 43:11.065
I don't know how long
I can keep doin' it.

43:17.465 --> 43:19.632
Me neither.

